\begin_layout Standard
The splitting of quantum mechanical energy levels in a weak magnetic field is best described by the Zeeman effect. Considering the semi-classical Bohr model for the atom, a simple energy level splitting 
\begin_inset Formula $\pm \mu_B B$
\end_inset

 (the 
\emph on
normal
\emph default
 Zeeman effect) is obtained. This is caused by the energy of the interaction of the magnetic moment 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_B$
\end_inset

 caused by the orbital motion of the electron with the external field 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

. However, this model does not include the spin magnetic moment and therefore it only correctly predicts energy level splitting when the total spin is 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

. A quantum-mechanical model of an atom incorporating the spin magnetic moment 
\begin_inset Formula $m_s$
\end_inset

 predicts an energy split of 
\begin_inset Formula $m_s g_L \mu_B B$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $g_L$
\end_inset

 is the LandÃ© g factor. Historically this phenomenon was called the 
\emph on
anomalous
\emph default
 Zeeman effect, because the spin interaction can not be explained classically. The anomalous Zeeman effect predicts an energy dependence on the quantum numbers 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $l$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $s$
\end_inset

, as verified in this report.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our experiments observed the normal Zeeman effect using the red (644 nm) transition line of a cadmium lamp. The anomalous Zeeman effect was investigated in the cadmium green (509 nm) transition line. A mercury lamp was utilised to observe the green (546 nm) and the blue (435 nm) transition lines. The lines were observed in two configurations: perpendicular to the magnetic field (both the 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 polarisation is visible) and along the field lines (only 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma$
\end_inset

 polarisation is visible). These measurements can fully verify the dependence of the splitting on spin, orbital angular momentum and total angular momentum.
\end_layout

