\begin_layout Enumerate

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "item: doppler"

\end_inset

 The spectral width of a line will be dominated by Doppler broadening. By assuming a Boltzmann distribution 
\begin_inset Formula $f(v) = \sqrt{\frac{m}{2 \pi k T}} e^{-\frac{mv^2}{2kT}}$
\end_inset

 for the particles, and by substituting the velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $v$
\end_inset

 from the Doppler shift equation 
\begin_inset Formula $f = f_0 (1+v/c)$
\end_inset

, we were able to recognise a Gaussian distribution with the FWHM of: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
      \delta \nu_{\mathrm{Dopp}} = \sqrt{\frac{8 k T \ln{2}}{mc^2}} \nu_0
  \end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is the mass of an atom, 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is the temperature and 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu_0$
\end_inset

 is the wavenumber of the peak of the distribution. By introducing the temperature of 
\begin_inset Formula $T = 500 \si{K}$
\end_inset

 into the equation, which is in line with the literature 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "doi:10.1098/rspa.1936.0108"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, we obtained an expected broadening in the range of: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
      \delta \nu_{\text{Dopp Cd red}} = 2.4 \si{m^{-1}} \label{eq: nu doppler}
  \end{equation}
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
      \delta \nu_{\text{Dopp Hg blue}} = 3.5 \si{m^{-1}}
  \end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "item: resolution"

\end_inset

 In theory, the resolution of a Fabry-Perot interferometer is related to the finesse 
\begin_inset Formula $F$
\end_inset

 of the instrument by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: instr resolution"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

. 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation} \label{eq: instr resolution}
      \delta \nu_{\text{instr}} = \Delta \nu_{\text{FSR}} F^{-1} = \frac{1}{2d} F^{-1}
  \end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta \nu_{\text{FSR}}$
\end_inset

 is the free spectral range of the instrument. According to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "FabryPerotEtalonGuide"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 we are expecting the reflectance of the mirrors of the Fabry-Perot to be 
\begin_inset Formula $R = 0.95$
\end_inset

. This is close enough to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

 to approximate the finesse to be given by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: finesse"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

. 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
      F = \frac{\pi R^{\frac{1}{2}}}{1 - R} \label{eq: finesse}
  \end{equation}
\end_inset

This results in a theoretical maximum instrumental resolution limit of: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
      \delta \nu_{\text{instr}} = 1.6 \si{m^{-1}}
  \end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "item: field"

\end_inset

 The magnetic field in the space between the iron cores was not perfectly uniform: edge effects make the field lines diverge and the field weaker at the centre of the gap between the cores. We were able to measure the variation of the magnetic field with the Gauss meter (Fig. 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:IvsB"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) and it is of the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $5 \si{mT}$
\end_inset

 for the highest magnetic fields achievable with this setup. We estimated the broadening resulting from the Zeeman effect caused by a spectrum of B-fields using equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: splitting"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to be at most: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
      \delta \nu_{\text{B}} = 0.5 \si{m^{-1}}
  \end{equation}
\end_inset

This value corresponds to a 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{eff} = \pm 2$
\end_inset

 value, and because it is much smaller than the other sources of line broadening, it will not significantly contribute to the final total resolution limit of the instrument. 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "item: flattness"

\end_inset

 The flatness of the mirrors is essential in obtaining a sharp image, as a deviation of just 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda / 2 \approx 250 \si{nm}$
\end_inset

 creates destructive interference. This is why we re-calibrated the mirror alignment after every set of measurements. Since we used a mirror surface with a dimension on the order of 
\begin_inset Formula $1 \si{cm}$
\end_inset

, any curvature with a radius lower than 
\begin_inset Formula $R \approx 400 \si{m}$
\end_inset

 will make measurements impossible. We were not able to estimate the flatness of the mirror, but results (section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: resolution measurement"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) indicated this plays an important role in determining the total instrumental resolution limit (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: nu tot prediction"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

). 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The resulting total resolution limit of the instrument was estimated by adding in quadrature the individual errors, and is predicted to be at most: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation} \label{eq: nu tot prediction}
    \delta \nu_{\text{total}} = \sqrt{\delta \nu_{\text{Dopp}}^2 + \delta \nu_{\text{instr}}^2 + \delta \nu_{\text{B}}^2} = 3.9 \si{m^{-1}}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Measurement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: measuremet"

\end_inset

 The fundamental equation that predicts the angular position of the maxima in a Fabry-Perot interferometer is: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    m = 2 \nu n d \cos{\theta} 
    \approx 2 \nu n d (1 - \theta^2/2)
    \approx 2 \nu n d (1 - \frac{r^2_m}{2f^2_c})
    \label{eq: order}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 is the interference order and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta  \approx r_m/f_c$
\end_inset

 is the angle. By subtracting equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: order"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for orders 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m + 1$
\end_inset

 we find that: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    r^2_m - r^2_{m+1} = f^2_c/\nu n d
\end{equation}
\end_inset

Equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: order"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for a different component 
\begin_inset Formula $\nu + \Delta \nu$
\end_inset

 is: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    m = 2 (\nu + \Delta \nu) n d (1 - \frac{r'^2_m}{2f^2_c})
\end{equation}
\end_inset

Combining these equations we find the splitting 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta \nu$
\end_inset

 to be: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \Delta \nu = - \frac{1}{2nd} \frac{r^2_m - r'^2_m}{r^2_m - r'^2_{m+1}}
    \label{eq: nu measurement}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $r_m$
\end_inset

 is the radius of the inner component, 
\begin_inset Formula $r'_m$
\end_inset

 is the radius of the outer component for the order 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $nd$
\end_inset

 is the optical path 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: d"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

. The radii of the rings in the interference pattern are measured using the Thor Labs software (Fig. 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig: d measurement"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

). The software is used to control shutter and gain of the camera to obtain the desired image brightness. We used the circular measure tool to manually fit circles to the maxima in the interference pattern and the software provides the radius of the circles in number of pixels.
\end_layout

