\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: Cd red"

\end_inset

 We first studied the 
\begin_inset Formula $5^1 D_2\rightarrow 5^1 P_1$
\end_inset

 transition for the cadmium red line. We used Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab: quantum_numbers"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: g eff"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to find the possible values for the effective g-factor to be 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{eff} = -1, 0, 1$
\end_inset

. This means that we expected the line to split into 3 components, with the splitting given by equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: splitting"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

. The theoretical value of the linear line splitting 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta \nu $
\end_inset

 as function of magnetic field 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{eff} = \pm 1$
\end_inset

 is: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \text{Theoretical value: } \frac{\Delta \nu}{B} = 46.7 \, \si{m^{-1}.T^{-1}}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

