\begin_layout Subsection
Electron charge to mass ratio
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: e/m ratio"

\end_inset

 An interesting use of the experiment performed in section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "sec: Cd red"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 is that we can employ the result 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "res: Cd red"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 to derive the charge to mass ratio of the electron. The formula for the Bohr magneton 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu_B = e \hbar / (2 m_e)$
\end_inset

 is introduced into equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: splitting"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, and after using that 
\begin_inset Formula $g_{eff} = 1$
\end_inset

 for this transition, we obtain: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \frac{e}{m_e} = 4 \pi c \frac{\Delta \nu}{B} = (-1.75 \pm 0.14) \times 10^{11} \si{C.kg^{-1}}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

This is in agreement with the theoretical value 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "CODATA2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \frac{e}{m_e} = -1.75882001076(53) \times 10^{11} \si{C.kg^{-1}}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

Interestingly, it is also possible to determine the sign of the electron charge. We used a beetle as reference for left hand polarised light. The beetle reflects bright green left-hand polarised light. Therefore we determined that the outer ring in the interference pattern were LH polarised and the inner ones were RH polarised. These measurements were done with a longitudinal setup, parallel to the magnetic field. We used a compass to determine that the B-field vector was in the direction of the photon momentum. Outer ring is higher energy (
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta \nu > 0$
\end_inset

), and 
\begin_inset Formula $ \Delta m_J = 1$
\end_inset

 corresponds to RH polarisation. By substitution into equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: splitting"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, this result confirms that electrons have negative charge.
