\begin_layout Section
Appendix - Energy levels and allowed transitions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec: theory derivation"

\end_inset

 One can find energy levels of an atom by considering the following Hamiltonian: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    H = H_{CF} + H_{RE} + H_{SO} + H_{ZE} \label{eq: atomic ham}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{CF}$
\end_inset

 is the interaction with the central field, giving the gross structure of the energy levels, 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{RE}$
\end_inset

 is the residual electrostatic perturbation, 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{SO}$
\end_inset

 is the spin-orbit interaction perturbation and 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{ZE}$
\end_inset

 is the interaction with an external magnetic field. In the weak field limit 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{ZE} \ll H_{SO} \ll H_{RE}$
\end_inset

 we can treat the Zeeman interaction 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{ZE}$
\end_inset

 as a perturbation to the fine-structure levels that arise from L-S coupling 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "Binney_Skinner_2015"
literal "false"

\end_inset

. The energy of the 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{ZE}$
\end_inset

 interaction comes from the precessional motion of the orbital and spin magnetic moments around the external field:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    H_{ZE} = \mu_B B \cdot (g_L L + g_S S) \label{eq: Hze}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $g_L = 1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $g_S = 2$
\end_inset

 are the g-factors for the orbit and spin respectively. 
\begin_inset Formula $|n l s j m_L >$
\end_inset

 is the natural basis for the perturbation because it diagonalises the Hamiltonian 
\begin_inset Formula $H_{ZE}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "foot2005atomic"
literal "false"

\end_inset

. This is because in order to calculate the energy perturbation of the energy level 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta E_{ZE}$
\end_inset

 one needs to take the time average of the operators in equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: Hze"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

. 
\begin_inset Formula $L \cdot B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S \cdot B$
\end_inset

 are not constants of motion, but 
\begin_inset Formula $J \cdot B$
\end_inset

 is. We consider projections of 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 along 
\begin_inset Formula $J$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    H_{ZE} = \mu_B B \cdot J(g_L \frac{|L \cdot J|}{|J|^2} + 
    g_S \frac{|S \cdot J|}{|J|^2}) \label{eq: Hze J}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

We cast the equation into the form 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: E lvl"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, where the LandÃ© g factor is 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq: gl2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \Delta E_{ZE} = m_J g_L \mu_B B \label{eq: E lvl}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

The splitting is a function of the j, l, and s quantum numbers: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    g_L = 1 + \frac{j(j+1)-l(l+1) +s(s+1)}{j(j+1)} \label{eq: gl2}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

